    "> reflect",
    "\n\nHere's what we did this session and what I'd note for next time:\n\n**What went well:**\n- Requirements-first approach — we clarified the exact selection logic (fastest arrival + earliest departure) before writing code\n- Caught the SL API's `calc_number_of_trips` max of 3 during local testing, before deploying broken code\n- The fix for the \"zero routes\" bug was a real improvement — iterating through multiple journeys means routes almost never get skipped now\n\n**Mistakes I made:**\n- The walking man emoji — I dropped the ZWJ characters when rewriting `process_route`. This is the second time this has bitten us. The `\\uXXXX` encoding should prevent it going forward\n- The favicon took 3 iterations (rotated, mirrored, then size change + format change). Generating pixel art programmatically without visual feedback is error-prone. For future icon work, SVG with emoji text is much simpler\n- I initially tried `calc_number_of_trips=5` without checking the API's limits, causing 400 errors\n\n**Things to remember:**\n- SL Journey Planner v2 max `calc_number_of_trips` is 3\n- The walking man emoji is `\"\\U0001f6b6\\u200d\\u2642\\ufe0f\\u200d\\u27a1\\ufe0f\"` — always use escape sequences\n- The `lambda/` directory name means you can't `from lambda.handler import` in Python — use `importlib.util` for local testing\n- `str_replace` can silently fail on whitespace mismatches when the file was rewritten — when in doubt, recreate the whole file\n\n**Current state:**\n- Lambda returns max 2 routes: fastest arrival + earliest \"leave home by\"\n- Fetches 3 trips per route to find catchable departures\n- Frontend unchanged — renders whatever the API returns\n- SVG favicon with 🚉 deployed\n- All deployed and live at jobbet.mulmo.name\n[Tool uses: none]",
